                        "pre-flood",

pre_lidar_dsm = rxr.open_rasterio(dsm_path, masked=True).squeeze()

# Create canopy height model (CHM)

In[23]:
# Create a list of labels to use for your legend
height_class_labels = ["Short trees",
                       "Medium trees",
                       "Tall trees",
                       "Really tall trees"]

# Create a colormap from a list of colors
colors = ['linen',
          'lightgreen',
          'darkgreen',
          'maroon']

cmap = ListedColormap(colors)

class_bins = [.5, 1.5, 2.5, 3.5, 4.5]
norm = BoundaryNorm(class_bins,
                    len(colors))

# Plot newly classified and masked raster
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))
im = pre_lidar_chm_class_ma.plot.imshow(cmap=cmap,
                                        norm=norm,
                                        # Turn off colorbar
                                        add_colorbar=False)
# Add legend using earthpy
ep.draw_legend(im,
               titles=height_class_labels)
ax.set(title="Classified Lidar Canopy Height Model \n Derived from NEON AOP Data")
ax.set_axis_off()
plt.show()
In[28]:
pre_dsm_path = os.path.join(
    'colorado-flood', 'spatial', 'boulder-leehill-rd',
    'pre-flood', 'lidar', 'pre_DSM.tif')
pre_dtm_path = os.path.join(
    'colorado-flood', 'spatial', 'boulder-leehill-rd',
    'pre-flood', 'lidar', 'pre_DTM.tif')

post_dsm_path = os.path.join(
    'colorado-flood', 'spatial', 'boulder-leehill-rd',
    'post-flood', 'lidar', 'post_DSM.tif')
post_dtm_path = os.path.join(
    'colorado-flood', 'spatial', 'boulder-leehill-rd',
    'post-flood', 'lidar', 'post_DTM.tif')

# Open with rioxarray (masked=True keeps NoData as NaN)
pre_dsm  = rxr.open_rasterio(pre_dsm_path,  masked=True).squeeze()
pre_dtm  = rxr.open_rasterio(pre_dtm_path,  masked=True).squeeze()
post_dsm = rxr.open_rasterio(post_dsm_path, masked=True).squeeze()
post_dtm = rxr.open_rasterio(post_dtm_path, masked=True).squeeze()
In[29]:
#Build the two CHMs (post  pre)
post_dsm = post_dsm.rio.reproject_match(pre_dsm)
post_dtm = post_dtm.rio.reproject_match(pre_dtm)

pre_lidar_chm  = pre_dsm - pre_dtm      #pre-flood CHM
post_lidar_chm = post_dsm - post_dtm   #post-flood CHM
In[30]:
# Compute the difference (post  pre)
chm_diff = post_lidar_chm - pre_lidar_chm
In[31]:
# CLassify the difference
chm_class = xr.zeros_like(chm_diff, dtype=np.int8)
chm_class = chm_class.where(chm_diff >= 0, -1)   # loss
chm_class = chm_class.where(chm_diff <= 0,  1)   # gain
chm_class_ma = chm_class.where(~np.isnan(chm_diff))
In[32]:
chm_colors = ['crimson', 'lightgray', 'limegreen']
chm_cmap   = ListedColormap(chm_colors)
chm_bins   = [-1.5, -0.5, 0.5, 1.5]
chm_norm   = BoundaryNorm(chm_bins, len(chm_colors))
chm_labels = ['Canopy loss', 'No change', 'Canopy gain']

f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))
im = chm_class_ma.plot.imshow(cmap=chm_cmap,
                              norm=chm_norm,
                              add_colorbar=False)
ep.draw_legend(im, titles=chm_labels)
ax.set(title="Classified Canopy Height Change (Post-flood  Pre-flood)")
ax.set_axis_off()
plt.show()
In[33]:
# DTM Difference
dtm_diff = post_dtm - pre_dtm
In[34]:
dtm_class = xr.zeros_like(dtm_diff, dtype=np.int8)
dtm_class = dtm_class.where(dtm_diff >= 0, -1)   # erosion
dtm_class = dtm_class.where(dtm_diff <= 0,  1)   # deposition
dtm_class_ma = dtm_class.where(~np.isnan(dtm_diff))
In[35]:
dtm_colors = ['royalblue', 'lightgray', 'saddlebrown']
dtm_cmap   = ListedColormap(dtm_colors)
dtm_bins   = [-1.5, -0.5, 0.5, 1.5]
dtm_norm   = BoundaryNorm(dtm_bins, len(dtm_colors))
dtm_labels = ['Erosion (lower)', 'No change', 'Deposition (higher)']

f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))
im = dtm_class_ma.plot.imshow(cmap=dtm_cmap,
                              norm=dtm_norm,
                              add_colorbar=False)
ep.draw_legend(im, titles=dtm_labels)
ax.set(title="Classified Terrain Change (Post-flood  Pre-flood)")
ax.set_axis_off()
plt.show()

Canopy change (CHM) what I did: I loaded pre- and post-flood DSMs and DTMs. I converted NoData to NaN so differences wouldnt be contaminated by missing values. I computed the canopy height model as CHM = DSM DTM for both time steps, then calculated change = post pre. I classified the change into three classes with a small tolerance (+-0.01) to catch numerical noise: negative (loss), no change, and positive (gain). I mapped the classes with a clear legend and added a descriptive title. Terrain change (DTM) what I did: I repeated the same process for the DTM surfaces, computing DTM change = post pre and classifying the result into negative / no change / positive using the same tolerance. I used a different color set to avoid confusion between the two maps and added a legend and title.
